# 1️⃣ Concept Teaching (Strict, Clear, GATE-Oriented)

---

# 🔹 Why Virtual Memory?

Programs may require more memory than physically available RAM.

👉 Virtual Memory gives illusion of:
[
\text{Large Main Memory}
]

using:

* Disk storage
* Address mapping

📌 Very important GATE topic.

---

# 🔹 Basic Idea

Only required parts of program are loaded into RAM.

Remaining stays on disk.

---

# 🔹 Address Space

---

## 🔹 Logical Address (Virtual Address)

Generated by CPU.

---

## 🔹 Physical Address

Actual RAM address.

---

# 🔹 MMU (Memory Management Unit)

Converts:
[
\text{Logical Address} \rightarrow \text{Physical Address}
]

📌 Key hardware component.

---

# 🔹 Paging (VERY IMPORTANT)

Memory divided into fixed-size blocks.

---

## 🔹 Terms

### Page

Block in virtual memory.

### Frame

Block in physical memory.

📌 Page size = Frame size.

---

# 🔹 Address Translation

Logical address contains:

[
\text{Page Number} + \text{Offset}
]

Page number used to access page table.

---

# 🔹 Page Table

Stores mapping:

[
\text{Page} \rightarrow \text{Frame}
]

---

# 🔹 Translation Lookaside Buffer (TLB)

A small cache storing recent page table entries.

👉 Speeds up address translation.

📌 Common numerical questions.

---

# 🔹 Page Fault

Occurs when required page not in memory.

Steps:
1️⃣ Trap to OS
2️⃣ Load page from disk
3️⃣ Update page table
4️⃣ Resume execution

📌 Expensive operation.

---

# 🔹 Effective Memory Access Time (EMAT)

Without TLB:

[
EMAT = 2m
]

(m = memory access time)

With TLB:

[
EMAT = h(t+m) + (1-h)(t+2m)
]

Where:

* h = TLB hit ratio
* t = TLB access time

📌 Very important formula.

---

# 🔹 Segmentation

Memory divided logically:

* Code
* Stack
* Data

Each segment has:

* Base
* Limit

---

# 🔹 Paging vs Segmentation

| Paging                    | Segmentation                    |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Fixed size                | Variable size                   |
| Physical division         | Logical division                |
| No external fragmentation | External fragmentation possible |

---

# 🔹 Fragmentation

---

## 🔹 Internal Fragmentation

Unused space inside allocated block.

Common in paging.

---

## 🔹 External Fragmentation

Free memory scattered.

Common in segmentation.

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

* Mixing page and frame
* Confusing internal/external fragmentation
* Wrong EMAT formula

